    overview_li6: '<strong style="color:#efeff1;">Hide Streamer</strong> \u2014 hides a streamer\u2019s cards across the home page, directory, sidebar, and search results so you no longer see them recommended.',

    // Settings
    note_manualMute: '<strong>Manual mute</strong> \u2014 if you mute a tab yourself using the browser, the extension will not unmute it. It only unmutes tabs that it muted itself.',
    s_muteInactive_title: 'Mute inactive tabs',
    s_muteInactive_desc: 'Mutes every Twitch tab that is not currently in the foreground. Tabs unmute automatically when you switch to them. Useful when you have multiple streams open and only want to hear the one you are actively watching.',
    s_switchOnAd_title: 'Switch tab on ad',
    s_switchOnAd_desc: 'When an ad starts on the <strong>Primary Tab</strong>, the extension automatically switches focus to another Twitch stream tab in the same window that is not playing an ad. Requires at least two Twitch stream tabs to be open. Non-stream pages (directory, search, home, etc.) are excluded as targets. See <em>Primary Tab</em> below for how to designate one.',
    s_returnOnAdEnd_title: 'Return when ad ends',
    s_returnOnAdEnd_desc: 'Works alongside <em>Switch tab on ad</em>. When the ad finishes on the Primary Tab, the extension switches focus back to it automatically. Interacting with the secondary tab while waiting does not affect this behaviour.',
    s_closeOnStreamEnd_title: 'Close tab when stream ends',
    s_closeOnStreamEnd_desc: 'Closes the tab automatically when the broadcaster ends their stream. A 5-second grace period is applied before closing to avoid false positives from brief interruptions. If the stream resumes within that window the close is cancelled.',
    s_autoReload_title: 'Auto-reload on crash',
    s_autoReload_desc: 'Detects stream crashes via Twitch\u2019s Error\u00a0#2000 message and video stall detection (playback frozen for 15+ seconds). When a crash is detected the extension first attempts to click Twitch\u2019s own retry button; if none is found it reloads the tab. Limited to 3 reloads per tab within any 10-minute window to prevent infinite reload loops.',

    // Primary Tab
    primaryTab_p1: 'The Primary Tab is the Twitch stream tab you designate as your main viewing tab. It is used by <em>Switch tab on ad</em> and <em>Return when ad ends</em> to know which tab to switch away from when an ad plays and which to return to once the ad is over.',
    primaryTab_p2: 'To set a tab as Primary, <strong>right-click anywhere on the Twitch page</strong> and choose <strong>Set as Primary Tab</strong> from the context menu. Only one tab can be Primary at a time \u2014 setting a new one automatically clears the previous.',
    primaryTab_p3: 'Once set, the tab title updates to <code>&lt;streamer&gt; - Primary</code> so you can identify it at a glance in the tab bar. The suffix is maintained even if Twitch updates the title dynamically (e.g. when the stream category or title changes). It is removed automatically when a different tab is made Primary or when the tab is closed.',
    primaryTab_note: '<strong>No automatic assignment</strong> \u2014 the Primary Tab is never set implicitly by clicking or navigating. You must assign it manually via the right-click menu.',

    // Do Not Mute
    dnm_p1: 'Do Not Mute (DNM) prevents the extension from muting a specific tab due to inactivity or any other content-related behaviour. <strong>Ads on that tab are still muted</strong> \u2014 this setting only protects content playback.',
    dnm_p2: 'To enable it, <strong>right-click anywhere on the Twitch page</strong> and open the <strong>Quiet Twitch</strong> submenu \u2014 the same menu used to set the Primary Tab. Check <strong>Do Not Mute This Tab (Ads are still muted)</strong> to enable it for that tab. Unchecking it removes the protection.',
    dnm_note1: '<strong>Per-tab setting</strong> \u2014 DNM is tracked individually for each tab and is cleared automatically when the tab is closed.',
    dnm_note2: 'When active, the tab title gains a <code>- DNM</code> suffix so you can identify protected tabs at a glance. If the tab is also the Primary Tab, <code>- Primary</code> takes precedence in the title.',

    // Hide Streamer
    h_hideStreamer: 'Hide Streamer',
    hideStreamer_p1: 'Hide Streamer removes a streamer’s cards from the pages you browse. Once hidden, the streamer no longer appears in home page recommendations, directory/category listings, the left sidebar’s recommended channels, search results, or the “suggests these channels” section under another streamer. Hiding is purely visual — it does not block, unfollow, or report the streamer on Twitch’s side.',
    hideStreamer_p2: 'To hide a streamer, navigate to their channel page and <strong>right-click anywhere on the page</strong>. Open the <strong>Quiet Twitch</strong> submenu and choose <strong>Hide Streamer: &lt;username&gt;</strong>. The option only appears when you are on a streamer’s channel page, not on the home, directory, or search pages.',
    hideStreamer_p3: 'To unhide a streamer, open the extension popup (click the Quiet Twitch toolbar icon) and expand the <strong>Hidden Streamers</strong> row. Each hidden streamer appears as a chip with a <strong>×</strong> button — click it to remove them from the list. Their cards reappear immediately on any open Twitch tab.',
    hideStreamer_note1: '<strong>Channel page redirect</strong> — if you click a direct link to a hidden streamer’s channel (e.g. from chat or an external site), the tab automatically redirects back to the Twitch home page.',
    hideStreamer_note2: '<strong>Synced across tabs</strong> — the hidden list is shared across all your Twitch tabs and persists between browser sessions. Adding or removing a streamer on one tab updates the others within a second.',

